#week-title("Three", "Reading the Distillate & Temperature Control")

=== Core Teaching

The distillate reveals the hidden nature of the plant. A milky or turbid
distillate may indicate that the fire was too high, forcing heavier fractions to
rise before their time. A clear, fragrant spirit is the sign of a controlled
operation.

Maintaining the correct degree of fire is non-negotiable. If you exceed the
correct temperature, you risk destroying the delicate "Mercury" of the plant.
Silence in the laboratory is your diagnostic: if you can hear the liquid boiling
violently, the heat is too high.

=== Topics This Week

- Sensory analysis of the hydrosol: color, scent, and clarity
- The critical importance of the thermometer
- Philosophical meaning of "ascending" and "descending" in the train

#inner-work[
